In Java, comparing strings using the equality operators (== or !=) is not recommended because these operators check if the two object references are identical, which is not the same as checking if the string contents are equal.

Instead, you should use the equals() method to compare strings. The equals() method compares the characters of two strings based on their Unicode code points, ignoring case differences. Here's an example:

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = new String("hello");

// Using the == operator will return false because the references are different.
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // Output: false

// Using the equals() method will return true because the string content is equal.
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2)); // Output: true
```

So, whenever you need to compare strings in Java, use the equals() method instead of the == operator.

